`IFormFile` buffers into memory by default. For large uploads, **stream the request body directly to disk** and raise the request-size limit.

### 1. Disable the default body size limit

```csharp
// Program.cs
builder.WebApplication.MapPost("/upload", HandleUpload)
    .DisableAntiforgery()
    .WithMetadata(new DisableRequestSizeLimitAttribute());

// Also raise Kestrel's cap in builder configuration:
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o =>
    o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024); // 2 GB
```

### 2. Stream the multipart body to disk section-by-section

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.WebUtilities;
using Microsoft.Net.Http.Headers;

async Task<IResult> HandleUpload(HttpRequest request)
{
    if (!request.HasFormContentType ||
        !MediaTypeHeaderValue.TryParse(request.ContentType, out var mt))
        return Results.BadRequest("Expected multipart/form-data");

    var boundary = HeaderUtilities.RemoveQuotes(mt.Boundary).Value;
    if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(boundary))
        return Results.BadRequest("Missing boundary");

    var reader = new MultipartReader(boundary, request.Body);
    MultipartSection? section;

    while ((section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync()) is not null)
    {
        if (!ContentDispositionHeaderValue.TryParse(
                section.ContentDisposition, out var cd) ||
            !cd.IsFileDisposition())
            continue;                       // skip non-file fields

        var trustedName = Path.GetRandomFileName();   // never trust the client name
        var savePath = Path.Combine("/tmp/uploads", trustedName);

        await using var fs = new FileStream(
            savePath, FileMode.Create, FileAccess.Write,
            FileShare.None, bufferSize: 81920);

        await section.Body.CopyToAsync(fs);           // streams in 80 KB chunks
    }

    return Results.Ok("Upload complete");
}
```

### Why this works

| Approach | Memory use | Mechanism |
|---|---|---|
| `IFormFile` | **Entire file in RAM** | Model-binding buffers the body |
| `MultipartReader` | **~80 KB** | Reads raw stream chunk-by-chunk |

### Key gotchas

- **Don't read `Request.Form`** anywhere before your handler — that triggers full buffering.
- **Validate early**: check file extensions / magic bytes, and enforce your own size cap by counting bytes in the `CopyToAsync` loop if needed.
- **If behind IIS**, also set `maxAllowedContentLength` in `web.config`:
  ```xml
  <system.webServer>
    <security>
      <requestFiltering>
        <requestLimits maxAllowedContentLength="2147483648" />
      </requestFiltering>
    </security>
  </system.webServer>
  ```

This streams the upload straight to disk with constant memory overhead regardless of file size.
